## Auth & Authorization

### Structure

Auth is always middleware ŌĆö never inline in route handlers. Think of it as a bouncer at the door, not a check at every table.

```ts
// Ō£ģ Route should look exactly like this
router.delete(
  '/users/:id',
  authenticate, // verifies token ŌåÆ sets req.user
  requireRole('admin'), // checks req.user.role
  deleteUserHandler // purely business logic, no auth checks inside
);
```

### JWT rules

- Access token: short-lived (15 min), stored in memory (never localStorage)
- Refresh token: long-lived (7 days), stored in httpOnly + Secure + SameSite=Strict cookie
- JWT payload: `{ userId, role, sessionId }` ŌĆö nothing sensitive (no email, no PII)
- Always validate `iss`, `aud`, `exp` claims on every request
- Rotate refresh tokens on every use ŌĆö invalidate old token immediately

### RBAC pattern

Define roles as an enum. Middleware enforces them ŌĆö services never check roles directly.

```ts
enum Role {
  USER = 'user',
  ADMIN = 'admin',
  SUPPORT = 'support'
}

// middleware/requireRole.ts
export function requireRole(...roles: Role[]) {
  return (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
    if (!roles.includes(req.user.role)) {
      throw new ForbiddenError('Insufficient permissions');
    }
    next();
  };
}
```

### Auth security checklist

- [ ] Passwords hashed with `bcrypt` (cost Ōēź 12) or `argon2` ŌĆö never plain or MD5
- [ ] Rate limit auth endpoints: max 10 attempts / 15 min per IP
- [ ] Refresh token rotation with revocation list (Redis or DB)
- [ ] CORS configured explicitly ŌĆö `origin: '*'` is never acceptable in production
- [ ] `helmet` applied to all Express apps

